column12: Measurement condition : Clear; Clear , No Precipitation , Very Light Wind
column13: Clear in close proximity to the gauge.  Approximately 50-60m downstream some dead trees laying partially in the channel.  Don't believe its enough to be causing the shift as the channel elevation change between the gauge and the tree is likely more than 30mm but it is not impossible.  Need to keep note of this area in the future.  Also some minor bank slumping just below the gauge on the on the right hand side see photos.
column14: Measured by wading with FT2 about 3m upstream of gauge.   Surveyed water level straight out from path in line with the mid channel and RHB sensors about 0.5m from the bank.  Used HG value closest to the MGH value as the gauge was reset mid measurement and cannot apply SRC to the first half the HG values.  HG values during the measurement very stable and 1230 MGH time is representative of water level conditions at time of measurement. Mid-section

column12: Measurement condition : Clear; Partly Cloudy , No Precipitation , Light Wind Blowing Upstream
column13:
-Consider clear but potential B conditions as substantial ice still visible, mainly downstream. Ice edge to edge ~50m downstream but looks bridged and water running below but not in contact as far as can be seen
-LHB obscured by ice but likely to shore/on rock up to the approximately the pipeline clearing then mostly clear bank to bank upstream of that.
column14: -FT2 wade just above pipeline clearing. -boulder influence unavoidable in transect. Difficult to find a clear section with minimal boulder influence and clear edges without ice hiding flow. -All three sensors assessed for MGH value. When average of 5 minute readings is used for all three (corection made for HG, HG2 as reset mid mmt) then the average is 6.721. Calculation on Field Review page. selected 15:50 DWL reading to input as saved time with same result. -@ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ -HG and HG2 reset, HG3 left as is (shown in comments in levels page) -Cut taken in line with path between gauge and creek. -Offsets HG (OTT) 6.49. HG2 (Bubbler) not noted, HG3 (OTT) 6.536 Mid-section

column12: Measurement condition : Ice; Clear , No Precipitation , Calm Wind
column13: Backwater conditions due to ice cover.
column14: Did not measure at the gauge.  Came with gear to measure in an open lead that is usually found near the gauge.  Instead found glaciated ice estimated to be 0.5 to 0.7m thick.  Ended up measuring approx 700m downstream of bridge in section that had many open leads like normally found at the gauge.  Had to brake some ice on both shores but tried to keep most of it from going under ice downstream and affecting velocities. @ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @

column12: Measurement condition : Ice; Cloudy , No Precipitation , Calm Wind Blowing Downstream
column13:
-varying ice coverage in reach visible from gauge. From 50% ice cover upstream to 100% in front of and downstream. Mostly open at bridge. 
-B conditions possible but several spot checks by chipping small hole in main flow show ice is bridged and not making contact with water surface,
column14: -FT2 wade ~10m upstream of gauge. Chipped transect through edge while main flow was still open. Most ice removed from transect was lifted out of channel onto remaining ice to minimize effect if caught under ice downstream -FT2 time was off by 5 minutes. Adjusted to true in eHSN. As recorded in .ft. -transect broken away ended up not perfectly perpendicular as a result of avoiding boulders at edges. Width taken after measurement by moving tape perpendicular to channel reduced width by less than 0.010m. Do not think this had much affect on bulk of flow as shots so close together and rod held perpendicular to channel. -Shift of -0.031 applied at time of measurement. Makes this measurement -0.0025m shift compared to last -@ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ -HG reset at 10:06, new offset 6.445.  -no SRC applied to MGH calculation. Other sensors left as is. -MGH based on logged readings. Did not have time to run levels again after measurement and did not have a rod in the water to take a second cut. -New BM installed. Lag bolt installed by BA in tree (2.5m from back right corner of gauge, 1.4m from NT05-130). Assume ground is not yet affected by frost heave based on SRC but unsure if this is the right time to establish a BM elevation? That's for a wiser operating tech to determine. -Existing lag bolt should be made inactive. Can not hold a stadia level next to it. Values used in this level run were recorded with the bubble around half in" Mid-section"

column13: Open water conditions.  Some leaf litter debris build up on the orifice line.  Don't believe it to be a significant source of backwater.  Appears to be a consistent shift in the past few measurements.  A new curve could likely be drawn at this time.

column12: Measurement condition : Clear; Clear , No Precipitation , Very Light Wind Blowing Downstream
column13: -Clear. No ice in channel or left on land
column14: -FT2 was 40minutes behind actual time during usage. Noticed after when compared to DWL time and noted when synced with GPS. -Wade infront of gauge, RHB at bottom of path from gauge to river.  -Boulders causing variable velocities. Surging. Willow brush in water on RHB.  -MGH values were logged under HG3. As that sensor was moved to HG (and HG3 is not available in eHSN), they have been entered as HG for calculation. -@ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ -All lines look they have moved and are pushed closer to the RHB. Left as is. Figured they were more stable near the edge than redeployed in highest flow in mid channel while creek is still in freshet conditions. -Cut taken at bottom of path from gauge to river. -SRC discrepancy between cuts is likely due to large surge on rod. Cut taken in calmest possible spot. -Offsets (reset at 12:10): HG: 6.450, HG2: 6.302, HG3: 6.358   Mid-section

column12: Measurement condition : Ice; Cloudy , No Precipitation , Very Light Wind
column13: Backwater conditions due to ice cover.
column14: Meausred approximately 12m upstream of gauge where the snow was sunken down.  Ice bridged half the mmnt section.  Water velocity visibly slower on half with ice and water touching.  Both tech's did not notice large angular velocities measured by Flow Tracker.  It seems legitimate though as most of the flow is trying to squeeze through the bridged section of the transect.  Used 0.6 method for bridged ice half of mmnt section and 0.5 depths for the other half where water running along bottom of ice.  @ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ Used old primary for the DWL which is unstable.  Surveyed the difference between it and the other ground rod to find the correction for the second reset.  HG3 is the stage value in the HG2 column.  SRC of 215 likely has a GC in it from using the moving primary for a reset in Oct of 2022. Mid-section
GC: 0.104m.  Adjusted DWL by 104mm for the movement of the control BM. HG2: 6.651

column12: Measurement condition : Clear; Partly Cloudy , No Precipitation , Calm Wind Swirling/Variable
column13:
-Clear. No obvious change to channel
-potential that at this low water level, the two conduits are acting as a miniature dam. Hard to capture on photos and not sure it has a measureable effect on stage but it does create a small pool that seems to alter the slope of the river, on the RHB, in front of the gauge. Not even close to enough to account for large SRC or shift value.
column14: -wade with FT2 about 50m upstream of cutline -low velocity panels confirmed as accurate. Caused by unavoidable boulders upstream of transect -No time for repeat mmt as needed to return to town for scheduled flight -@ Uncertainty: IVE method, 2-sigma value (2 x Uncertainty Value reported in *.ft File). @ -DWL used as MGH for now. Large SRC and unsure if OTT reliable or visible movement in Bubbler trace needing correction. -Total station was having battery issues. Was able to complete circuit but confirmation levels run with conventional to ensure that large SRC was not due to equipment error. 0.002m difference between them. -Cut taken in line with path and orifice block for total station. About 2m downstream for conventional (to assist sightline through bushes). Both upstream of mentioned mini-pool from conduit Mid-section

BACKWATER CONDITIONS; SOME BRIDGED ICE AND VARIABLE THICKNESSUNDER THICK LAYER OF SNOW. AFTER DETERMINED Q SECTION AT ORIFICE UNSUITABLE, CAUSED ICE DAM BELOW ORIFICE POOL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT 14:15 MST, TRIED DRILLING AT GAUGE BUT NOW A POOR CROSS SECTION WITH LOWER WATER LEVEL.  THEN TRIED DOWNSTREAM AT ORIFICE POOL, BUT ANGULAR FLOW AS CHANNEL VEERED TO LHB WITH CHANNEL SLOPE AND WE CREATED A BIT OF AN ICE/SNOW DAM AND LIKELY BACKED WATER UP SOMEWHAT (SEE PHOTOS).  WE THEN MEASURED ABOVE PIPELINE ON ONLY SUITABLE OPTION WITH COMPLETE ICE COVER STRONG ENOUGH TO WORK FROM.  SEVERAL PANELS BRIDGED ICE.  AFTER Q MEASUREMENT, SWAPPED OUT N2 TANK AND PURGED ORIFICE. -HOT WATER USED ON METER -NO SLUSH -AVERAGE ICE THICKNESS = 0.13 m.   -MAX % Q @ P4 = 16% Sources:Manual
